But Sir Richard has totally mistaken the meaning of this “ dai-ing Roman :’' which, indeed, is not very extraordinary, for almost all the commentators have done the same. Far-*from attacking the eternal intelligence and first cause of all things, in conse- quence of the moral and physical evils of the world, he accounts for them briefly here, and more fully in the 5th book, by adverting to the nature of matter itself. This, the Epicureans, in common with all the other Greek phibsophers, conceived to have been eternal, and uncreated. By its very nature, it is subject to mutability in all its concrete forms; and from its incessant changeS, decompositions‚ and re- combinamus, proceed all the evils we meet with in the world.
